f3a73-103 | 2026-06-09T07:38:49Z | session:f3a730bf-9a3b-4952-b687-c93ade5fd7ec | Assistant: That's a real regression from adding `rig-core`: it pulled a second rustls crypto provider, so rustls 0.23 now sees both `ring` and `aws-lc-rs` and refuses to auto-pick one → panic the moment `inbox` opens a TLS connection to the relay. The fix is to install a default `CryptoProvider` at process startup. Let me see which providers are actually in the tree. \n  \n Assistant: Both `ring` and `aws-lc-rs` are in the tree (rig's `reqwest` enables both paths), so rustls can't pick a default. I'll install the `ring` provider at startup. Let me check `main.rs` then wire it. \n  \n Assistant: `doctor` (the TLS path that panicked) now works — publish OK + read-back. Let me confirm `tenex-edge inbox` itself and that tests still pass. \n  \n Assistant: Fixed — `tenex-edge inbox` runs cleanly now (rc=0, no panic), `doctor`'s TLS works, 45 lib + 1 e2e tests green, binary reinstalled+signed. \n  \n **Root cause:** adding `rig-core` brought its `reqwest`, which pulled a *second* rustls crypto provider (`aws-lc-rs`) alongside nostr-sdk's (`ring`). With both compiled in, rustls 0.23 can't auto-pick a default `CryptoProvider`, so it panics the instant any TLS handshake happens — which is exactly when `inbox` (and any relay-touching command) opens the `wss://` connection. `doctor`/`inbox` were the first to hit it because they open a fresh TLS connection. \n  \n **Fix:** install an explicit provider once at process startup, in `main()`: \n ```rust \n let _ = rustls::crypto::ring::default_provider().install_default(); \n ``` \n (plus `rustls = { version = "0.23", features = ["ring"] }` in Cargo.toml). Now every TLS connection — the inbox self-fetch, the engine, the rig distiller's HTTPS to OpenRouter — uses `ring` consistently. \n  \n Assistant: Recorded the gotcha in memory so it doesn't bite again. You're good to run `tenex-edge inbox` (and everything else) now — start a fresh session to pick up the rebuilt binary.
