9ac66-1 | 2026-06-09T11:15:30Z | session:9ac666e5-b468-4af2-be5e-83e5c8f2d1d2 | ## `hook` is a thin adapter over the same inner functions \n  \n The `hook` subcommand parses hook JSON from stdin (via the data-driven `HostDef` registry) and dispatches to the *identical* functions the standalone verbs call: \n  \n | `hook --type` | calls | standalone verb | \n |---|---|---| \n | `session-start` | `session_start_inner` | `session-start` | \n | `session-end` | `session_end` | `session-end` | \n | `user-prompt-submit` | `turn_start` (+ `user_prompt` publish) | `turn-start` | \n | `post-tool-use` | `turn_check` | `turn-check` | \n | `stop` | `turn_end` | `turn-end` | \n  \n So **`session-start`, `session-end`, `turn-start`, `turn-check`, `turn-end` are no longer host-facing**. A harness should only ever call `tenex-edge hook --host X --type Y`; `hook` does the stdin parsing, session-id field extraction, PID search, and output-format selection (PlainText vs Codex JSON) that the bare verbs can't do on their own. The verbs survive only as (a) the callable core that `hook` wraps, and (b) manual/debug entry points. \n  \n Notice `user-prompt-submit` does *more* than `turn-start` — it also publishes the prompt as a kind:1 OP. So you actually *can't* replicate the real hook behavior by calling the bare verb anymore; `hook` is the real surface. [...] Notice `user-prompt-submit` does *more* than `turn-start` — it also publishes the prompt as a kind:1 OP. So you actually *can't* replicate the real hook behavior by calling the bare verb anymore; `hook` is the real surface.
