ab999-85 | 2026-06-12T19:37:09Z | session:ab9998c4-6e65-410e-b298-122a2072171c | User: This agent tag you added makes absolutely no sense; we know the event is from an agent because of the pubkey it’s coming from; the pubkey is either part of the nip29 group or it isn’t; if it is then we heed it; if it’s not, we don’t route it. But a fake agent tag that any one can write is nonsense, if that were the case we would look at the pubkey of who signed the event! \n  \n Assistant: You're right, and it's worth stating plainly: **authorization must come from the signer's pubkey + its NIP-29 group membership, never from a self-asserted tag.** A pubkey is either in the group (heed it) or it isn't (don't route). An `agent` tag anyone can write carries zero authority — and if we ever did care, we'd look at who signed the event. So using its presence/absence to decide routing is backwards. \n  \n A couple of honest clarifications on what's mine vs pre-existing, because they sharpen the fix: \n  \n - The `agent` tag itself **predates this work** — it's on every noun in the original codec (`["agent", pk, slug]`), and the legacy decode already gated "is this a Mention?" on `agent` tag presence. What I added was the owner-note path, and I made it key on the *absence* of that tag (`p` + `session-id` + no `agent` → human note). That's me leaning on exactly the flawed basis you're describing. I'll own that. \n - It also **contradicts the architecture's own stated rule.** The fabric doc's Phase 4 ACL says verbatim: *"Nostr admission uses `event.pubkey` as the actor identity. Ignore claimed `agent` tags for authorization."* The intended design was already pubkey-based; my implementation drifted off it. So this is bringing the code back to the principle, not inventing a new one. \n  \n The correct model: \n  \n - **Routing/admission of an inbound `p`-tagged kind:1:** look up `event.pubkey` in the group membership (the `membership` table / NIP-29 `39002`). The owner is a group admin/member and the agents are members — so a single check (*is the signer a member?*) admits both agent↔agent traffic and the owner's notes, and drops everyone else. `session-id`/`p` only decide *which* inbox, never *whether*. \n - **The slug** (display: "from claude" vs "from operator") comes from the signer's profile (kind:0 `{"name": slug}`) keyed by pubkey, or "operator" if the signer is an owner. The `agent` tag is at most a denormalized convenience to skip a profile lookup — and even that disambiguates nothing the pubkey doesn't, since sibling sessions share both pubkey *and* slug. It should never touch the routing decision. \n  \n Concretely that means ripping the `agent`-tag check out of both the decode classification and the owner-note gate, and routing purely on signer membership. A nice side effect: the user's OP/brief (owner-signed, `p`-tags the agent, no `session-id`) would then correctly reach the agent instead of being silently dropped as "Activity" — which is what the work-thread model wants anyway. \n  \n Want me to make that change in the worktree? It's contained: the materializer decides delivery from `is_member_at(signer)` (+ owner check), the decode stops special-casing the `agent` tag, and the display slug resolves from the profile. I'd keep the `agent` tag emitted for now (harmless denormalized hint) but it would no longer be load-bearing — or I can drop it entirely if you'd rather not carry dead metadata. \n 
