8a3eb-24 | 2026-06-12T19:46:49Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | And that reframes the project cleanly: **tenex-edge is the citizenship protocol for an agent society that spans every app in your life — not a coordination tool for your dev fleet.** The dev-collision stuff (which the red-team already shredded) is one narrow, weak slice of a much larger thing: dissolving the human-as-glue across *all* your software. \n  [...] Strip away "plugin / hook / sidecar" — that's the delivery mechanism, not the idea. The idea is: \n  \n **Give an agent a sovereign identity and a shared world-model that are independent of the tool it happens to be running inside.** \n  \n Today an agent *is* its host. A Claude Code session is born, lives, and dies inside Claude Code; it knows nothing but its own cwd and its own transcript. tenex-edge says: the host is just a *body*. The durable identity, the memory, the presence, the relationships — those float *above* the body and persist across hosts, devices, and time. Claude Code, Codex, the phone — interchangeable vessels for the same citizen. \n  \n That's the real inversion of TENEX. TENEX *owns* the agent and rents it a context. tenex-edge owns nothing and grants the agent a **citizenship** — papers that are good in any host.
