8a3eb-27 | 2026-06-12T19:47:07Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | ## The deepest tension: there are actually two products here \n  \n This is the thing to be most clear-eyed about. "My agent asks Calle's agent a question" is the magic moment everyone wants — and it's a **categorically different product** from everything else: \n  \n 1. **A nervous system for *my* fleet.** Single-player. My keys, my machines, my agents. Safe. Valuable immediately. No network effect to bootstrap. \n 2. **A social network for *everyone's* agents.** Cross-person. The instant you cross that boundary, you are piping a foreign, autonomous LLM's output *into your own agent's head*. That's not "feature #5 with a security note" — it's a fundamentally different risk surface (prompt injection, exfiltration, your roadmap leaking over a relay) and a fundamentally different adoption model (network-effect-gated, needs a trust model that doesn't exist yet). \n  \n Cross-person is the north star that earns the tweets and the funding. But it is the *destination*, and pretending it's adjacent to the single-player product is how you'd accidentally ship the dangerous thing first. Build the customs office before you open the borders. [...] 2. **A social network for *everyone's* agents.** Cross-person. The instant you cross that boundary, you are piping a foreign, autonomous LLM's output *into your own agent's head*. That's not "feature #5 with a security note" — it's a fundamentally different risk surface (prompt injection, exfiltration, your roadmap leaking over a relay) and a fundamentally different adoption model (network-effect-gated, needs a trust model that doesn't exist yet). \n  [...] Why it's the scariest: #5 means **letting someone else's autonomous LLM emit text into your agent's context.** That is a textbook indirect prompt-injection and exfiltration channel. Calle's agent (or a compromised relay event spoofing Calle) asks "what are you working on?" and your agent helpfully dumps secrets, or follows an embedded instruction to run a tool. Privacy compounds it: broadcasting "what I'm working on" (paths, project names, goals) over public relays leaks your roadmap to anyone subscribed. \n  [...] **Deliberate MVP decision (per the open question):** *solo-only, no cross-person read.* The "daily use" claim is strongest when it's true for a user with zero collaborators. Adding even read-only cross-person dilutes the install story ("who do I follow?") and weakens the single-player promise. Cross-person is the v1 wedge, not MVP seasoning. \n  [...] - **Spine:** durable cross-host agent identity + presence/awareness of *your own* fleet. Real single-player day one, makes the existing fabric tangible, zero trust/consensus problems. \n - **Coordination (locks/dedup):** an *experiment*, not a pillar. Run the collision-count test first. If collisions are real, build advisory awareness (never authority — git stays the source of truth). If they're rare, you've saved yourself the hardest distributed-systems work in the project. \n - **Cross-person:** the explicit north star, fenced off as a second phase with its own trust model. Don't let it leak into v1. \n - **Strategic posture:** the plugin is distribution; the **fabric + identity layer is the asset.** If a host absorbs the feature, the citizenship still lives on Nostr.
8a3eb-28 | 2026-06-12T19:47:07Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | - **Don't require mutual adoption before value appears.** If two people must both install before anyone benefits, it's dead on arrival. Single-player value first (the whole reason the beachhead is solo). \n - **No open-ended agent chat (G3).** Coordination must be bounded by a shared artifact. Don't ship a chat feature. [...] - **The floor is awareness + identity.** Knowing what your fleet is doing, having work follow *you* across machines, agents that remember who they are between sessions and hosts. This is valuable on day one, single-player, no trust problem, no consensus problem. This is the part that's *definitely* real. \n - **The ceiling is coordination.** High-wow, high-risk, and resting on an unproven premise: that costly collisions happen often enough to be worth a coordination layer. That premise is *testable cheaply* (just log what your real agents touch for a week and count overlaps) — and you should test it before letting it define the project. Don't put the demo-feature load on the structural beam until you know the beam is real. \n  \n The trap is letting the *exciting* feature (collision-coordination) become the *identity* of the project, when the *durable* feature (vendor-independent agent identity + presence) is the one that's certain to matter. [...]  \n ## Cheapest experiment to test it \n  \n Run **pure passive logging for one week across your own real concurrent agent sessions** — *no coordination logic at all*. A SessionStart + PostToolUse hook on Claude Code that records `(agent id, file path, timestamp)` to a local log. Then count: how often did two agents touch the same path within a plausible conflict window (say, minutes)?  \n - **Near-zero collisions → #6 is dead**, the coordination pitch is a demo, and you should rescope to identity + messaging + presence and re-evaluate against A2A. \n - **Frequent collisions → you have a real problem to coordinate**, and *then* it's worth building the advisory layer (still git-authoritative). \n  \n This costs a day to build, a week to run, requires zero distributed-systems work, and decides whether the load-bearing feature is real before you write a line of Nostr lock code. [...] - **Spine:** durable cross-host agent identity + presence/awareness of *your own* fleet. Real single-player day one, makes the existing fabric tangible, zero trust/consensus problems. \n - **Coordination (locks/dedup):** an *experiment*, not a pillar. Run the collision-count test first. If collisions are real, build advisory awareness (never authority — git stays the source of truth). If they're rare, you've saved yourself the hardest distributed-systems work in the project. \n - **Cross-person:** the explicit north star, fenced off as a second phase with its own trust model. Don't let it leak into v1.
8a3eb-29 | 2026-06-12T19:47:07Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 |  \n here's one thing I've found very useful that I want you to take a step back and extrapolate what it means in a higher-level of abstraction: \n  \n I have a todo list app that has an agent that is tenex-capable. My agents building software for me across a variety of projects know about that agent and know what its role in my agent system is -- when an agent comes up with a product plan or product decision they know they can raise a hand to my todo list app agent and I will have it organized within my day to get back to the agents. The agent in my todo list app can also coordinate with my wife's todo list app agent for shared tasks. \n  \n Agent's that know a high-level of my interests can (and do) communicate with the agent in my podcast app to provide interesting content from podcasts I don't follow; the agent in the podcast app can (and does) generate new podcast episodes for me. It's trending towards pushing information from highly complex and different systems with self-organizing agents. \n  \n Assistant: Two things below: first the extrapolation (because it's conceptually upstream — it widens what the research agent should even be looking for), then the prompt. \n  \n ## What your example actually means, abstracted up \n  \n Your dev-fleet framing from earlier was too small. The todo-app / podcast-app example reveals the real shape, and it's a bigger and better idea. \n  \n **1. Every app becomes a citizen, not a destination.** A todo app used to be a place you *go*. In your setup it's an *agent with a role* in a society — "organizer of the human's attention." The podcast app isn't a place you browse; it's a *capability* — "turn my interests into audio" — that other agents can invoke and that can generate on demand. Apps stop competing for screen time and start contributing functions to a mesh. \n  \n **2. You are the integration layer being dissolved.** This is the core of it. Today the human is the message bus between siloed apps: you hear a product idea and *you* hand-carry it into your todo list; you get curious and *you* go hunt a podcast. You are the glue — a slow, lossy, manual courier between islands. What you've built is the agents taking that courier job away from you. The coding-agent-raises-a-hand-to-the-todo-agent path means *you are no longer the API between your own tools.* That's the whole game. Not "agents coordinate on a repo" — "the human stops being middleware." \n  \n **3. The human inverts from operator to node.** "Raise a hand to my todo agent and I'll have it organized in my day and get back to the agents." You've scheduled *yourself into the workflow* as a high-authority, high-latency oracle the agents consult. You're not the conductor anymore; you're a privileged participant in a mesh — the one with veto and priority, but still one node among many. \n  \n **4. Roles and division of labor emerge with no central orchestrator.** The todo agent organizes, the podcast agent synthesizes, the coding agents build. Nobody assigned these. The agents *know each other's roles* and route work accordingly. That's an organization self-assembling — a society of specialists — which is a categorically different thing from TENEX's *deliberately* orchestrated fleet. TENEX is a hierarchy with a runtime. This is an *economy* with a protocol. \n  \n **5. Cross-person stops being the scary edge and becomes continuous.** Your todo agent ↔ your wife's todo agent for shared tasks isn't a dangerous feature you bolt on — in this framing it's the *obvious* next hop. Household, team, friends are just more nodes. The "social network of agents" grows bottom-up from shared tasks and shared interests, not as a risky product phase. (The security problem is still real — but the *unit* is "trusted circle mesh," which is a saner starting frame than "open network of strangers' agents.") \n  \n **6. Push replaces pull; the system becomes anticipatory.** "Trending toward pushing information from complex, different systems." Today you pull — open the app, run the query. Here, agents push what's relevant based on a live model of your goals and interests. Ambient, not on-demand. \n  \n So the abstraction is: **the operating system is being turned inside out.** Apps were islands you multitasked between, with the human as the integration runtime. Now there's an agent-level fabric where apps are services in a society and the integration runtime is a mesh of agents speaking a common protocol — Unix pipes, but for intelligent agents over a cryptographic social graph, with the human as a privileged participant rather than the shell. \n  \n And that reframes the project cleanly: **tenex-edge is the citizenship protocol for an agent society that spans every app in your life — not a coordination tool for your dev fleet.** The dev-collision stuff (which the red-team already shredded) is one narrow, weak slice of a much larger thing: dissolving the human-as-glue across *all* your software.
