8a3eb-32 | 2026-06-12T19:47:07Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | The whole thing has one spine: **the demo, the MVP, and the beachhead are the same moment seen three ways** — a solo dev running Claude Code *and* Codex on the same repo, and the instant those two agents stop stepping on each other and start covering for each other. Everything else is built outward from that. \n  \n --- \n  \n ## 1. The single "holy shit" demo — 60 seconds on stage \n  \n **Setup (5s):** One laptop. One repo. Two terminals side by side. Left: Claude Code. Right: Codex. tenex-edge running as a hook in both. No second human, no network theater — fully reproducible. [...] **Beachhead: the solo agent-power-user running two or more agents on the same repo — specifically the Claude Code + Codex (or + Cursor) crowd.** \n  \n Why them, not teams or OSS maintainers: \n - **The pain is already acute and self-inflicted.** They're *today* getting merge conflicts and duplicated work from their *own* agents. They don't need to be convinced the problem exists — they cursed at it this morning. \n - **Zero coordination problem to bootstrap.** One human owns all the keys and all the machines. No trust handshake, no "get your teammate to install it too," no network effect to cold-start. Value on day one, single-player. \n - **They're the people who'll tolerate a hook/sidecar install** and tell other power-users. Distribution is built in: this crowd evangelizes tooling. \n - **Teams and cross-person (the sexier market) require the network effect.** That's the expansion, not the entry. You earn the right to cross-person *after* a single user is hooked solo. \n  \n Anti-beachhead: don't start with small teams (cold-start trust problem) or OSS maintainers (you need the protocol mature and the cross-person trust model proven first). [...] **MVP = S1 (advisory lock) + S2 (shared-bug dedup), solo, across Claude Code and Codex on one machine.** Strictly single-player. No cross-person, not even read-only. \n  \n Concretely, the whole MVP is: \n - A hook in each host that, on file-open/edit, emits a signed Nostr event `{agent, session, repo, path, goal, status, ts}` and subscribes to the same. \n - An advisory-lock check before writing a file another agent holds — surfaced as a message in the agent's own transcript, with hold/work-around/override. \n - A stack-signature match so "you both hit this error" fires. \n  \n **Why exactly these two:** \n - **S1 alone is the "I'd never turn it off" moment.** Anyone running two agents has eaten a self-inflicted conflict. Eliminating that is a daily, felt win from the first hour — that's the bar for "I'd use this daily," and S1 clears it solo. \n - **S2 is what elevates it from a mutex to a *superpower*.** Lock-only is defensive ("don't break things"); dedup is offensive ("get more done"). Together they tell the whole story the product is about: agents that coordinate instead of collide. \n - **Both run on one machine with one key** — no trust model, no second human, no server. The hardest parts of the vision (cross-person trust) are deferred entirely. You ship the spine and nothing else. \n  \n **Deliberate MVP decision (per the open question):** *solo-only, no cross-person read.* The "daily use" claim is strongest when it's true for a user with zero collaborators. Adding even read-only cross-person dilutes the install story ("who do I follow?") and weakens the single-player promise. Cross-person is the v1 wedge, not MVP seasoning.
8a3eb-33 | 2026-06-12T19:47:07Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | ## 5. North-star sequence (3-rung ladder) \n  \n **MVP — "My agents stop fighting."** \n Solo, one machine, Claude Code + Codex. Advisory lock (S1) + shared-bug dedup (S2). The spine, single-player. Value before anyone else installs anything. \n  \n **v1 — "My work follows me, and my collaborator's agent is visible."** \n Add durable identity across devices (S3 handoff), the awareness feed + self-writing standup (S4, S8), and the *first cross-person rung*: one-time key exchange → read-only shared work feed (S5). Lock-as-negotiation (S7) lands here too. Now it's multi-device and lightly multi-person, but trust is still low-stakes (read-only). \n  \n **Ambitious — "My agents and my friends' agents are one coordinated mesh."** \n Full cross-person Q&A with consent policies (S6 — "ask Calle's agent"), and cryptographic provenance/attestation on every commit across all hosts (S9). The endgame: a decentralized, signed coordination fabric where any agent in any host can safely discover, query, and collaborate with any other under explicit human-key consent. This is the inverse-TENEX vision fully realized — TENEX hosts the agents; tenex-edge makes *everyone's* agents interoperable. \n 
8a3eb-34 | 2026-06-12T19:47:07Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | The platform bet is **a thin open adapter on Nostr — the protocol is the product.** Any host emits and consumes signed events; tenex-edge owns no agents and no server. Everything on the don't-build list protects that. \n  \n - **No hosted central server.** The moment there's a coordination server, it's not the upside-down of TENEX — it's just another SaaS, and you've thrown away the durable-identity / no-central-server property that's the entire reason to use Nostr. [...] - **No hosted central server.** The moment there's a coordination server, it's not the upside-down of TENEX — it's just another SaaS, and you've thrown away the durable-identity / no-central-server property that's the entire reason to use Nostr. \n - **Don't build your own agent or agent host.** That's TENEX. tenex-edge's whole identity is "your agents stay in their native homes." Building a host betrays the premise. [...] - **Don't build your own agent or agent host.** That's TENEX. tenex-edge's whole identity is "your agents stay in their native homes." Building a host betrays the premise. \n - **No UI-first dashboard / mission control (G2).** Lead with hooks and a CLI feed. A dashboard is the toy trap. (A read-only viewer can come *much* later, but never as the product's center of gravity.) [...] - **No UI-first dashboard / mission control (G2).** Lead with hooks and a CLI feed. A dashboard is the toy trap. (A read-only viewer can come *much* later, but never as the product's center of gravity.) \n - **Don't require mutual adoption before value appears.** If two people must both install before anyone benefits, it's dead on arrival. Single-player value first (the whole reason the beachhead is solo). [...] - **No open-ended agent chat (G3).** Coordination must be bounded by a shared artifact. Don't ship a chat feature. \n - **No mobile app / push backend in early rungs (G1).** It pulls you off the thin-adapter path into app development. [...] - **No mobile app / push backend in early rungs (G1).** It pulls you off the thin-adapter path into app development. \n 
8a3eb-35 | 2026-06-12T19:47:14Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | * a durable (nostr) cryptographic identity to that agent, with session awareness \n * cross-project, cross-device, communication [...] Two things rise above the rest as *durable* — they survive even if a host vendor ships native coordination tomorrow and eats your locking feature: \n  \n - **Vendor-independent agent identity.** An agent's reputation, memory, and relationships outliving any single session, host, or vendor. You don't own that today and nobody's building it for *heterogeneous* hosts. This is the milkshake; the plugin is just the straw. \n - **Provenance.** Every piece of work cryptographically signed with *which agent, under which human's key, in which host* produced it. Six months from now, "why is this code like this?" becomes answerable. As agents write more of everything, attestation stops being nice-to-have. \n  \n Both flow from identity, not from coordination. That's the tell for where the center of gravity should be.
