f3a73-112 | 2026-06-12T19:49:39Z | session:f3a730bf-9a3b-4952-b687-c93ade5fd7ec | Per session process. [...] Assistant: This is the decisive finding, and it changes the transport approach — I need to be honest about it. \n  \n **NMP is not a lean transport library — it's a full cross-platform app *kernel*.** Every relevant crate (`nmp-nip01`, `nmp-nip42`, even via `nmp-network`) funnels through `nmp-core`: an Elm-architecture single-actor-thread kernel with FFI, flatbuffers codegen, a subscription planner, and reactive UI projections. It's built for SwiftUI/Compose/wasm apps with live subscriptions bound to views — not for a headless fire-and-forget CLI daemon that publishes a heartbeat and tails a project. Embedding it would mean adopting dispatch/reconcile + flatbuffers for "send a kind:1," and it would dominate this build instead of producing working tested code. \n  \n The good news: **the codec/transport seam in M1 exists exactly for this.** The wire protocol is identical regardless of library, so a tenex-edge agent is equally legible to the fabric, and NMP's real future value (`nmp-nip29`/`nmp-marmot` as alternative codec *shapes*) stays reachable behind the seam later. So I'll build transport on the lean, standard `nostr`/`nostr-sdk` stack now to get a real working+tested system, behind a `Transport` trait, with NMP documented as the intended swap-in. I'm flagging this prominently — it's an empirical deviation from "use NMP" that I'll keep correctable — but per the goal I'm not halting on it.
f3a73-113 | 2026-06-12T19:49:39Z | session:f3a730bf-9a3b-4952-b687-c93ade5fd7ec | Assistant: That's a real regression from adding `rig-core`: it pulled a second rustls crypto provider, so rustls 0.23 now sees both `ring` and `aws-lc-rs` and refuses to auto-pick one → panic the moment `inbox` opens a TLS connection to the relay. The fix is to install a default `CryptoProvider` at process startup. Let me see which providers are actually in the tree. \n  \n Assistant: Both `ring` and `aws-lc-rs` are in the tree (rig's `reqwest` enables both paths), so rustls can't pick a default. I'll install the `ring` provider at startup. Let me check `main.rs` then wire it. \n  \n Assistant: `doctor` (the TLS path that panicked) now works — publish OK + read-back. Let me confirm `tenex-edge inbox` itself and that tests still pass. \n  \n Assistant: Fixed — `tenex-edge inbox` runs cleanly now (rc=0, no panic), `doctor`'s TLS works, 45 lib + 1 e2e tests green, binary reinstalled+signed. \n  \n **Root cause:** adding `rig-core` brought its `reqwest`, which pulled a *second* rustls crypto provider (`aws-lc-rs`) alongside nostr-sdk's (`ring`). With both compiled in, rustls 0.23 can't auto-pick a default `CryptoProvider`, so it panics the instant any TLS handshake happens — which is exactly when `inbox` (and any relay-touching command) opens the `wss://` connection. `doctor`/`inbox` were the first to hit it because they open a fresh TLS connection. \n  \n **Fix:** install an explicit provider once at process startup, in `main()`: \n ```rust \n let _ = rustls::crypto::ring::default_provider().install_default(); \n ``` \n (plus `rustls = { version = "0.23", features = ["ring"] }` in Cargo.toml). Now every TLS connection — the inbox self-fetch, the engine, the rig distiller's HTTPS to OpenRouter — uses `ring` consistently. \n 
