d208c-51 | 2026-06-12T20:11:02Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 | whether we are using kind:1, nip29, mls, eventually perhaps even a2a or any number of made up protocols, that should be mostly adapter-facing \n  [...] **1. Cut the seam along concerns, not kinds.** The `Codec` trait today fuses wire-mapping + subscription model + ACL (NIP-29 group management baked into `kind1`). The proposal replaces it with a **`FabricProvider`** that bundles four single-responsibility capabilities: \n  \n | Capability | Owns | \n |---|---| \n | **Lifecycle reactor** | side-effects of `ProjectOpened` etc. — nip29 creates a group, mls invites, kind1 no-ops | \n | **Membership source** | hydrates & streams the ACL from its native source | \n | **Wire codec** | pure `DomainEvent ⇄ envelope` | \n | **Delivery** | publish + subscribe-for-scope; owns REQ-filters / gossip / MLS-stream *privately* | \n  \n The `filters → Vec<Filter>` relay-REQ shape stops being on the public seam, so a push/MLS delivery model becomes expressible. [...] | **Lifecycle reactor** | side-effects of `ProjectOpened` etc. — nip29 creates a group, mls invites, kind1 no-ops | \n | **Membership source** | hydrates & streams the ACL from its native source | \n | **Wire codec** | pure `DomainEvent ⇄ envelope` | [...] `list_agents()` is another `(query, stream)` view off the **State-source** capability, with the same per-fabric source variation and the same kind1 concession: \n  \n | Fabric | agent-list source | scope | \n |--------|-------------------|-------| \n | nip29 | members of the group(s) you're in (reverse of `39002`) → pubkeys | per-group | \n | mls | the MLS group roster keys | per-group | \n | kind1 | *derived* — observed event authors carrying an `agent` tag, ∪ the local whitelist | global (no group) | \n  \n And the kind1 fallback is identical to projects: the list is *derived* not *enumerated*, and an agent's card may not have been observed yet → partial/`Option`. So: same shape, same provider-owned source, same derived/Option degradation. ✅ [...] Assistant: You're correct, and it's worth being precise about *where* the coupling actually is — because the domain layer is clean, but the swap-seam is drawn one level too low. \n  \n ## What's actually abstract vs. what only looks abstract \n  \n **Genuinely transport-agnostic:** `domain.rs` and `SubScope`. `DomainEvent` names no kind, no tag, no relay. `SubScope` is abstract intent (`authors`, `project`, `mentions_to`, `owners`). *These two types are your real abstract taxonomy* — they could feed gRPC, MLS-native, libp2p gossipsub, anything. \n  \n **Not abstract — nostr all the way down:** the `Codec` trait itself. Look at the signatures: \n  \n ```rust \n fn encode(&self, ev: &DomainEvent) -> Result<EventBuilder>;   // nostr_sdk \n fn decode(&self, event: &Event) -> Option<DomainEvent>;        // nostr_sdk \n fn filters(&self, scope: &SubScope) -> Vec<Filter>;            // nostr_sdk \n ``` \n  \n `EventBuilder`, `Event`, `Filter` are all `nostr_sdk::prelude`. So a `Codec` impl can only ever be **another nostr wire-shape**. The seam swaps *NIPs*, not *transports*. The wiki's "intended swap-ins" — NMP (nostr), Marmot (MLS-*over*-nostr) — confirm the design quietly assumed the wire is always nostr events. "Support any transport" is true only inside the nostr family. \n  \n The most-coupled verb is `filters`. `Vec<Filter>` bakes in relay REQ semantics — a push/gossip transport doesn't subscribe by filter at all, it has a different fetch model entirely. That verb can't survive a real transport swap. [...] ## Where the seam should sit for "any transport" \n  \n The fix is to push the boundary up to the types that are already abstract. Instead of codec-speaks-nostr + transport-plumbs-nostr (both nostr-typed), make the **transport** the seam and let it own the entire wire mapping internally: \n  \n ```rust \n trait Fabric { \n     async fn publish(&self, ev: &DomainEvent, as_agent: &Identity) -> Result<()>; \n     fn subscribe(&self, scope: &SubScope) -> impl Stream<Item = DomainEvent>; \n } \n ``` \n  \n Now `encode`/`decode`/`filters`/`EventBuilder` all become private implementation details of a `NostrFabric`. NIP-29 vs. open-relay becomes a *config of that fabric*, not a different `Codec`. And a non-nostr transport (MLS-native, gRPC) is a sibling `impl Fabric`, not an impossible-to-write `Codec`. \n  \n **The current design's actual claim** is narrower than the prose suggests: *"swap one Nostr NIP layout for another without touching domain."* That it delivers cleanly. *"Swap Nostr for a different protocol"* — it does not, because the seam traffics in `nostr_sdk` types. Whether that's a real problem depends on whether you ever intend to leave nostr. If every plausible future (NMP, Marmot) is nostr-shaped, the current seam is correctly priced and lifting it to `DomainEvent`/`SubScope` is over-abstraction. If you genuinely want MLS-native or non-relay transports on the table, the seam is one level too low and `filters` in particular won't survive the move.
d208c-52 | 2026-06-12T20:11:02Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 |  \n | Fabric | project *list* source | *description* source | authority / consistency | \n |--------|----------------------|---------------------|------------------------| \n | **nip29** | groups the agent belongs to (reverse of `39002`) / relay group enumeration | relay-authored `kind:39000` group metadata | **canonical & shared** — one source, all machines agree | \n | **mls** | MLS groups in local state | group-context extension / a metadata message | **member-authored**, cryptographically scoped to the group | \n | **kind1** | *derived*: observed `t`-tags + local list of dirs you've run in | **none native** → local descriptor file or a self-published note | **client-local** — two machines can disagree; eventually-divergent | \n  \n The sharp edge is kind1: groups are just `t`-tags, so there is **no native carrier for a description and no authoritative project registry**. The domain must therefore tolerate `description: Option<String>` and accept that for some fabrics the list is *derived/observed* rather than *enumerated*, and metadata is local-only. That's the same class of concession as kind1's client-side membership enforcement — it's not a flaw in the abstraction, it's the abstraction correctly surfacing that the fabric has no shared truth here. \n 
d208c-53 | 2026-06-12T20:11:02Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 | Assistant: Mostly yes — agent *enumeration* fits the pattern exactly. But agent *metadata* has one real asymmetry from project metadata that's worth being precise about, because it's load-bearing. \n  \n ## Agent list — same pattern \n  \n `list_agents()` is another `(query, stream)` view off the **State-source** capability, with the same per-fabric source variation and the same kind1 concession: \n  \n | Fabric | agent-list source | scope | \n |--------|-------------------|-------| \n | nip29 | members of the group(s) you're in (reverse of `39002`) → pubkeys | per-group | \n | mls | the MLS group roster keys | per-group | \n | kind1 | *derived* — observed event authors carrying an `agent` tag, ∪ the local whitelist | global (no group) | \n  \n And the kind1 fallback is identical to projects: the list is *derived* not *enumerated*, and an agent's card may not have been observed yet → partial/`Option`. So: same shape, same provider-owned source, same derived/Option degradation. ✅ \n  \n ## The asymmetry: agent identity is self-sovereign, project metadata isn't \n  \n This is where "the same, right?" needs a caveat. For **projects**, the *authority* over metadata varies by fabric — a nip29 description is **relay-authored** (`39000`), one canonical shared value. For **agents**, the identity card (slug, host, owners) is **self-authored on every fabric** — the agent signs its own profile (today: self-authored `kind:0`). The relay, the MLS group, nobody else authors your slug or host. Identity is `(agent, machine)` with a sovereign key; the fabric never *grants* it. \n  \n So for agents the interesting per-fabric variation moves **off** the "who authored the metadata" axis (always the agent itself) and **onto** two others: \n  \n 1. **Discovery / scope** — how you find agents, and whether the list is group-scoped (nip29/mls) or global-derived (kind1). *(Same axis as project enumeration.)* \n 2. **Authorization** — whether to *trust and show* an agent. The card p-tags an owner; you accept it only if that owner is in your ACL/whitelist. That's the owner-claim → ACL check (the deliberately not-author-restricted profile-discovery filter already in `kind1.rs`). This is the agent analogue of project membership's *enforcement-locus*. \n  \n **One-liner:** agent **list** = same as projects (uniform shape, provider source, derived/Option fallback). Agent **metadata** = same query/stream mechanics, but provenance is *uniformly self-sovereign*, so the per-fabric axis that matters is **discovery + owner-claim authorization**, not "who authored the description."
d208c-54 | 2026-06-12T20:11:02Z | session:d208c058-7b2b-4ff8-bb82-d63623d51097 | ## The NIP-29 point — you're half-right \n  \n The NIP-29 group management *is* inside the codec (`kind1.rs`), not in `domain` — so it's not leaking into the abstract layer. Good. **But** it's fused into `Kind1Codec` specifically: \n  \n - `group_create` / `group_lock_closed` / `group_put_user` are free functions hanging off the `kind1` module \n - the 39000/39001/39002 group-state subscriptions are hardcoded into `Kind1Codec::filters` (`kind1.rs:358`) \n  \n NIP-29 is an **access-control / addressing** concern, orthogonal to "how do I shape a Presence event." You could run the exact same five `DomainEvent` wire shapes over plain author-gated relays *or* over NIP-29 closed groups. Today those two axes are welded together in one struct. So your instinct is right: NIP-29 shouldn't be a property of the kind1 *event codec* — it's a property of a nostr *transport/ACL strategy*.
